            <h2>Syntax Overview</h2>
            <p>In this module you have learned a few important features of Old English syntax: the structure of clauses and sentences. 
                Syntax is a large topic, and we've really just scratched the surface here. But understanding a little about Word Order,
                Correlations, and other features of Prose Style should allow you to tackle original texts such as the one below that ends 
                this module.
            </p>
            <h3>Word Order</h3>
            <p>We learned that word order in Old English is more flexible than in modern English due to the relatively extensive system of 
                inflections. Subject-Verb-Object is still the most common order, but Verb-Subject order occurs regularly in clauses introduced
                by adverbs such as <em>þa - then</em> or <em>nu - now</em>. In relative clauses introduced by the relative pronoun '<em>þe - 
                which/that/who</em>', the verb usually goes to the end of the clause. These three word orders are illustrated in the sentence
                below:'<em>Se wicing eode to his scipe, þe on Temese muþan wæs, and þa ferde he to Lundene - the Viking went to his ship, which 
                    was in the Thames estuary, and then he travelled to London'.
                </em>'

            </p>
