            <h3>Correlation</h3>
            <p>One common feature of Old English prose is the use of correlating pairs - words that work together to structure a sentence. 
                Some of the most common are <em>þa...þa</em> (meaning 'then...when', or 'when...then'), and <em>swa...swa</em> (sometimes meaning 
                as...as). With correlating pairs such as <em>þa...þa</em>, the adverb 'then' can be distinguished from the conjunction 'when' based
                on word order: after 'then', the verb will come before the subject, as in <em>þa se biscop to Eoferwic com, þa forþferde he - when 
                    the bishop came to York, (then) he died'.
                </em>
            </p>
